@node Overview "Overview"

This is a conversion of the 1977 3W board game "Africa", for up to 5
players. Players can be controlled by human or Amiga. SAS/C and StormC
source code is included.

In this game each player takes the role of one of the powers attempting to
establish or maintain a sphere of influence in the southern half of the
African continent. By interfering in the economic stability and political
alliances of nations, and by subsidising them, the players attempt to
extend their political control of Africa, while diminishing the control of
their opponents.

There is the opportunity to set up governments in favour of the players,
encourage revolutions, start wars between the African nations and even
introduce armies of the player-powers into the continent.
@endnode

@node Requirements "System Requirements"

@{b}Hardware@{ub}             Required       640x512x64 capability
                                     (AGA or graphics card)
                     Recommended    Flixer fixer
                                    Keyboard with numeric keypad
@{b}Firmware@{ub}             Required       Kickstart R3.0+
@{b}Software@{ub}             Required       OS3.0+
                     Recommended    OpenURL.library
                                    TCP/IP stack

The user's preferred screen mode, game mode, etc. are stored in the
Africa.config file.

If the Africa.config file does not exist, you will be asked to select
your preferred screen mode. At least 640*512 in 64 colours is required.
There is no benefit in selecting more colours than this.

If the WormWars.font is available, it will be used, otherwise Topaz 8 is
used. Note that the correct version of WormWars.font is 264 bytes; the
older version is malformed and should not be used.
@endnode

@node Arguments "Startup Arguments"

@{b}CLI Arguments@{ub}

                                   @{b}Africa@{ub}

@{b}Format:          Africa@{ub}
                 [SCREENMODE]
                 [[FILE=]<@{i}savedgame@{ui}>]]

@{b}Template:@{ub}        SCREENMODE/S,FILE

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}         To run the Africa game.

@{b}Specification:@{ub}

    SCREENMODE:  This allows you to choose a new screenmode at startup,
                 even if an Africa.config file exists.

    <@{i}savedgame@{ui}>:  the pathname of your saved game to load at
                 startup. This is taken exactly as entered; an '@{b}.africa@{ub}'
                 extension is not automatically appended.

    ?:           displays the command line argument format.

The order of the arguments is interchangeable.
@endnode

@node Controls "Controls"

There is a 'Message Delay' slider. The positions of this slider correspond
with informational message reading delays as follows:

    1st    0.2s
    2nd    0.4s
    3rd    0.8s
    4th    1.2s
    5th    1.6s
    6th    2.0s
    7th    Infinite

Note that this does not affect the "Round # of #" prompts (because they
provide a unique opportunity to restart and/or save the game), or any
prompt which requires a user response.

When finished reading an informational message, pressing RETURN or the
spacebar will continue the game. You can hold down the key to skip
multiple messages.

You can load and play a previously saved game from the title screen (or
CLI). You can save the current game, and/or restart the game, at the start
of each turn. The game is automatically saved (to PROGDIR:Autosave.africa)
at the start of each turn. We suggest using an extension of ".africa" for
saved game files.

The game is played with a combination of mouse and keyboard input.
Counters and hexes are selected with the mouse. Numeric amounts require a
response from the keyboard. Most other things can be done with either
device. You can use the left mouse button for "Yes" and the right mouse
button for "No" and "Esc" (except that you cannot use the right mouse
button for quitting the game).

Information about the hex currently under the pointer is displayed as you
move the mouse around the board. To get detailed information about a
particular hex, press Help when the pointer is over the desired hex.

To find out about declared wars you need to use the appropriate menu item
(Help|Declared Wars...). In the declared wars window, white means "at
war", black means "not applicable", and other colours mean "at peace".

When moving, you are able to undo your most recent move by pressing the
Backpspace key.

Note that using colonial names does not change the counters (ie. flags and
names on the counters will not change).

The 'Watch Amiga movements?' options controls whether you see each
individual move made by Amiga-controlled armies.

At the bottom right corner of the screen, you can see the current purposes
of the left and right mouse buttons.
@endnode

@node Credits "Credits"

@{b}Credits@{ub}

The AmigaOS/MorphOS conversion of Africa was programmed by James Jacobs of
Amigan Software. Special thanks to Stephen Thomas for providing scans of
the rules, board and counters. The AmigaOS 4 port was done by James Jacobs
and Samir Hawamdeh.

The original board game was designed by Martin Edwardes and published by
3W (World Wide Wargames) in "The Wargamer" issue #3 (1977).

