@node Rulebook "Rulebook"

@{b}BACKGROUND AND STRATEGY@{ub}

In the thirty-odd years since the end of the 2nd World War two things have
affected the international political scene perhaps more than any others:
the alignment of the rich, technologically advantaged nations of the
North into power blocs; and the break-up, by peaceful or violent means, of
the worldwide empires of the Western European nations. In 1945 the world
was ruled largely by Britain, France, the USSR and the USA with about a
hundred other, minor, nations. Now the scene has changed to a world
divided by ideologies, and further divided by national aspirations into
nearly two hundred nations.

An excellent example of this is the African continent. Before the war only
four governments existed on the continent: Liberia, a small, incredibly
poor state created for American niggers wishing to return to Africa,
Ethiopia, subsequently annexed by Italy in 1935; and Egypt and South
Africa, both well within the British sphere of influence. The rest of the
continent was divided between the western European nations. However during
the 2nd World War the British found it necessary to promise post-war
independence to India, and this was granted in 1948. The precedent had
been set and spread across the world like wildfire. National movements
mushroomed in Malaya, Indochina, the Middle East, and throughout Africa.
Some countries achieved independence by violent means, others were offered
it as the economic advantages of the territory faded, or as the costs of
maintaining armies grew. A wave of liberalism in Europe, too, reduced the
desire to hold onto empires. Another factor was the growing ascendence of
the USA in the Western world: Marshall Aid gave a powerful economic lever
to the USA and created strong links, culturally and economically, across
the Atlantic. Mainland Europe withdrew from its empires into an internal
compact from which the EEC emerged, and Britain maintained its economic
position, as the Empire died, through the Commonwealth. By the early 1960s
the African continent had taken on more or less its present political
shape.

Meanwhile, outside Africa, other events were dictating the relationship
between the victors of the war. By 1949 the civil war in China was over.
This had been a war between the National Republic led by Chiang Kai Shek
and the People's Republic led by Mao Tse; a war that had started in the
late 20s after the collapse of Imperial China. It was, at least in part,
suspended during the 2nd World War, when both sides had attacked the
Japanese, but broke out again when Japan surrendered. USA and Britain had
supported the Nationalist forces, while the USSR had supported the
Communists, who won. This did not create another member of the Soviet
bloc, as the West feared and the USSR hoped, but a new and independent
bloc.

In Europe the Western Allies had been surprised by the appearance of the
Berlin Wall, and the collapse of the wartime alliance. Both sides drew up
their armies along the "Iron Curtain across Europe", and the Cold War
began. And in America the appearance of a Communist country on their
doorstep (Cuba) aroused fear and suspicions of Soviet intentions,
culminating in the Cuban missile crisis of 1963. The creation of a new
Germany by the Western Allies, when it had been agreed that Germany would
never rise again, posed a traditional threat to the USSR. The ideological
war was on, with Macarthy witch-hunts, anti-Stalinist purges,
denunciations and verbal attacks from both sides, and a race to persuade
the non-aligned nations of the world to the appropriate ideological point
of view. The situation was further complicated in the late 1960s by a
strong China wishing to extend its influence beyond Southeast Asia, and by
the sudden growth of importance of Africa as an economic supplier to
Europe, as the USA began using more of its own raw material.

So it was that the break-up of the European empires and the confrontation
of the powers has come together in the African continent in the 1970s. The
USA attempts to expand the doctrines of the Free Market over the
continent, and to gain diplomatic leverage with military positions like
the Cape; the USSR attempts to expand the area within its sphere of
influence while China, a relative newcomer to the continent, is intent on
proving the greater success of their form of communism, while uniting the
3rd World under their leadership. France and Britain are intent on
securing markets and advantageous economic terms.

This is the situation around which the game of "Africa" is based. It
attempts to illustrate the struggle between the powers for control in the
continent, and to do this the African nations must be considered to be
politically subordinate to the Player-powers. This is not a reflection
upon the political acumen of African leaders, some of whom juggle the
superpowers with a skill and daring that makes the politicians of the
richer nations appear blunderers by comparison; it does, however, reflect
the reliance of the African nations on the Powers for weapons, economic
aid and international trade - and it is necessary to make a playable game.

The players, representing the Powers, attempt to create an area on the
continent under their control while preventing their opponents from doing
likewise. This can be done in many ways. The player can attempt to woo the
African nations by Political Influence, a process corresponding to the
real life gifts of weapons, economic aid, favourable economic terms, etc.
He can attempt to disrupt the Internal Stability of nations, causing
revolutions, which may or may not lead to government under his Political
Influence (the equivalent of economic sanction, political intervention,
and the operations of the security organisations of the Powers). Or he can
attempt to influence events more directly with military operations by
African nations under his political control against other African nations,
a process that has not occurred recently in the southern half of Africa
(the area of the board) but which has occurred between Libya and Egypt,
and between Somalia and Ethiopia.

While attempting to expand his hegemony the player must also protect what
he already possesses. For this he must again consider both Internal
Stablity and Political Influence. But he also has available the
possibility of putting in a strong leader or junta to lead the country,
thus reducing the chance of revolution, and preventing another player from
wooing the country away on the Political Influence table. He can also pour
money into the national treasury to enable the country to build more
armies, or declare war; and he can even put his own troops into the
country (the equivalent of the Cubans in Angola), although the UK does not
have this option.

The tactics of this game vary with the number of players, but certain
things apply in all games. The USA has, at the beginning of the game, a
decision to make: whether to make South Africa a base for immediate
military operations, or to support the Loyal Zairean forces against the
rebels. (This game was completed in early 1977, before the Katangese
collapse.) South Africa, being the strongest nation on the board, is often
prone to attacks on its Stablity and Political alliance, but Zaire is in
the centre of a potentially highly disputed area - you pays your money and
you takes your choice. The USA must also choose carefully its moment to
establish Namibia as an independent state, as there are additional victory
points possible here.

The USSR has strength in both Angola and Mozambique, although it is rare
that it can get to use them both. Of the two Angola seems to be most used
- in support of the Zaire Rebels and against South Africa, but Mozambique
has the better military position. In the multi-player game it is possible
for the USA to win in the first turn - I won't tell you how, you can work
it out - this should be prevented if the conditions arise; "Africa" is a
game of diplomacy, and constant contact should be kept with other players.

Here are the modified rules as used in this version. The original rules
are @{"here" link Original}.

@{b}RULES@{ub}

@{b}1. Introduction.@{ub} In this game each player takes the role of one of the
powers attempting to establish or maintain a sphere of influence in the
southern half of the African continent. By interfering in the economic
stability and political alliance of nations, and by subsidising them, the
players attempt to extend their political control of Africa, while
diminishing the control of their opponents.

There is the opportunity to set up governments in favour of the players,
encourage revolutions, start wars between the African nations and even
introduce armies of the player-powers into the continent.

@{b}3. Initial Setup.@{ub} Each player selects one of the Player Powers.
The following Powers should be in play:

    @{u}No. of players    Powers@{uu}
          2           USA, USSR.
          3           USA, USSR, China.
          4           USA, USSR, China, France.
          5           USA, USSR, China, France, UK.

Then the African nations are set up. The starting positions for the
Political Influence and Internal Stability markers, the initial forces and
any Leaders or Juntas are set out in the table below.

                         Political    Internal     Armed
    @{u}Country              Influence    Stability    Forces    Leader/Junta@{uu}
    South Africa           USA 4          7          10      -
    Namibia                -              -          -       -
    Botswana               UK 3           4          2       -
    Rhodesia-Zimbabwe      USA 4          7          4       USA Leader
    Mozambique             USSR 5         5          4       USSR Junta
    Angola                 USSR 7         4          4       USSR Junta
    Zambia                 UK 2           5          4       UK Leader
    Malawi                 UK 3           5          1       -
    Gabon                  France 5       5          1       France Junta
    Congo                  France 4       4          2       France Leader
    Zaire (loyal)          USA 5          3          4       USA Leader
    Zaire (rebel)          USSR 4         3          2       -
    Tanzania               China 7        6          4       China Junta
    Uganda                 0              3          2       UK Leader
    Kenya                  UK 4           6          4       UK Leader

Armed forces and Leaders and Juntas are always placed by the player with
Political Influence. (Uganda is [initially] placed by UK.) When there are
fewer than 5 players the pieces of the non-playing Powers are placed by
the Amiga.

@{b}3.1. Stacking.@{ub} Only one army or intervention unit may occupy a hex,
although a Leader or Junta unit may (in fact, must) occupy the same hex as
an army.

@{b}4. Order of Play.@{ub}

    a. PLAYER POWERS PHASE:
        i.   Player income;
        ii.  Order writing;
        iii. Order reading and application.
    b. AFRICAN COUNTRIES PHASE:
        i.   Random event;
        ii.  National income;
        iii. Expenditure;
        iv.  Movement of forces;
        v.   Attacks;
        vi.  Supply;
        vii. Revolution Stability check.
    c. LEADER/JUNTA ELIMINATION.

@{b}4.1. Player Powers phase.@{ub} In this phase the players attempt to influence
the African nations. This represents the political interplay of the
powers.

@{b}4.1.1. Player income.@{ub} Each player has the following income each turn, @{i}plus@{ui}
the result of a die roll ($1-$6):

    USA    $15;
    USSR   $14;
    China  $13;
    France $12;
    UK     $11.

The Player Power's treasury is increased the appropriate number of points
on the National Treasury table, adding on any amounts left from last turn.

@{b}4.1.2. Order writing.@{ub} Each player decides, secretly, his expenditure
for that turn. He can spend on:

    Political Influence;
    [Internal] Stability;
    Leaders or Juntas;
    Intervention Units;
    transfers to treasuries of other Players or of African nations.

@{b}4.1.2.1. Political Influence.@{ub} Political Influence (PI) affects the
control that a Player Power can exercise over an African nation. The cost
is $4 per point. Markers can be moved up the player's PI track, or down an
opponent's, depending on the orders given. If the movement takes the
marker over the zero point then it moves up the track of the buying player.
Any nation's PI can be moved no more than 3 points in one turn, either up
or down, although players may buy more points to counteract opponents'
orders. It cannot go below zero or above 10.

@{b}4.1.2.2. Internal Stability.@{ub} This affects the strength of African nations
and their tendency to revolution. To alter the position of a national
marker on the Internal Stability (IS) table either up or down costs $4.
Any player can buy points to affect any African nation, regardless of the
political affiliation. Any one marker can be moved no more than 3 points
in one turn, either up or down, although players may buy more points to
counteract opponents' orders, and it cannot go above 10 or below zero.

@{b}4.1.2.3. Leaders and Juntas.@{ub} These affect the tendency to revolution of
African nations, and the exertion of Political Influence by the Powers.
They cost $2 each to place, and can only be placed in nations over which
the placing player has Military or Political control. One one Leader or
Junta may be placed in any one country, although two may be placed in a
country in Revolution so long as one only is on each side. They can only
be placed on African armies, and must remain stacked with the army. An
African nation with a Leader/Junta (L/J) unit unit can go up no [Political
Influence] track but that of the L/J owner. It can rest at zero. They have
no effect on combat. They can be destroyed by:

    the army they are stacked with being destroyed;
    a random event (see 4.2.1);
    a successful L/J elimination.

@{b}4.1.2.4. Intervention units.@{ub} These repesent the actual military presence
of soldiers of the Power involved (eg. Cubans in Angola). They cost $4 for
the USA and USSR to build and maintain each turn, and $2 for China and
France. UK does not have an Intervention unit (IU), the others have only
one. They must be placed on or next to a city over which the player
involved has Military control, and must draw their supply from that city,
or one also under Military control. They should be "attached" to the
forces of the country in which they have been placed, and move and attack
with that country's forces. The African nation does not maintain them,
however, as this is done by the Player Power. Their loss does not affect the
IS of the nation to which they are attached. They always have full
strength in combats (see IS table). They are removed, at the order reading
stage, if:

    a. The player has not maintained them that turn.
    b. The nation to which they were attached is no longer under Military
       control.

If they are removed as above or by combat they can be rebuilt on the
following turn.

@{b}4.1.2.5. Treasury Transfers.@{ub} These are simple to carry out. An order
stating the amount and receiver is written, and in the order reading stage
the amount is deducted from the player's Treasury and added to the
receiving Treasury. There are no limits on this, except that African
nations can never transfer money out, only in.

@{b}4.1.3. Order reading and application.@{ub} When all the players are satisfied
with their orders, they read them out, in turn. The orders are applied
subject to the restrictions given above.

@{b}4.2. African Countries Phase.@{ub} In this phase the African nations are played
one by one, under the guidance of the players. The player with Political
control plays the nation; if no one has PC of the nation then it can only
maintain its armies, which is handled by the Amiga. The nations are played
in the order printed on the board (South Africa to Kenya) with the rebels
played at the end. N.B. Each nation conducts all its activities before the
next begins.

@{b}4.2.1. Random Event.@{ub} The is a 1 in 6 chance that a random event has
occurred for that nation; if so, the die is rolled. This is indexed on
the Random Events table, and the result carried out.

@{b}4.2.2. Nation Income.@{ub} Each city owned by the African nation, whether on
home or foreign soil, gives an income of 2 to its owner, except Zomba and
Libreville which give an income of 1. This is added to any amount already
in the National Treasury.

@{b}4.2.3. Expenditure.@{ub} The African nations can now spend on the following
items:

    maintenance of national forces    ($1 per army in homeland,
                                       $2 per army in foreign lands);
    raising new forces                ($2 per army);
    declaring war                     ($3 per declaration);
    simply keeping an unspent reserve

(a list of costs is on the board). Nations in joint operations calculate
their expenditures separately. A nation can never exceed the amount in its
National Treasury; loans or gifts at this stage are not allowed.

@{b}4.2.3.1. Maintenance of National Forces.@{ub} If not maintained the appropriate
army is removed. IS falls one point for every army lost this way.

@{b}4.2.3.2. Raising New Forces.@{ub} This can only be done if the nation is under
Political or Military control. The new army must be built on or next to
home cities and not in enemy zones of control. The maximum number of
armies of a nation (ie. its number of pieces) cannot be exceeded. Raising
new forces does not raise the IS.

@{b}4.2.3.3. Declaring War.@{ub} This can only be done by a nation under Military
control. Without such control, operations against other nations (movement
and attacks) other than within the home borders cannot be carried out.
Wars are declared against nations, not against geographical countries; if
a nation occupies more than one country one declaration of war is
sufficient.

@{b}4.2.4. Movement of Forces.@{ub} Only nations under political or military
control can do this. Each army moves up to 5 hexes, subject to the
following restrictions:

     a. An army must stop when it enters an opponent's zone of control.
     b. It may not cross national boundaries unless the nation owning the
        unit has declared war on the nation across the boundary, or the
        owning nation also owns all the cities across the boundary, or the
        nation across the boundary is under a friendly military control
        and is amenable to such an incursion.
     c. Cities do not affect movement.
     d. Pieces do not have to move.

@{b}4.2.4.1. Zones of Control.@{ub} These are the 6 hexes around the hex an army is
in. They do not extend anywhere the army cannot move to. Enemy cities can
be captured by being placed under a friendly Zone of Control (ZOC), but if
there is an opponent's ZOC also extended over the city it must be occupied
by a friendly army.

@{b}4.2.5. Attacks.@{ub} Attacks can be made against pieces on neighbouring hexes;
it is not necessary to make all possible attacks. An attack can be made by
several pieces against one, or one against one, but not one against
several, or several against several. Each piece can attack only once per
turn, although it may be attacked several times. For a nation to attack
enemy armies in its homeland it must be under at least Political control.
For a nation to attack enemy armies outside its homeland it must be under
Military control and have declared war on the enemy.

The result of the attack is calculated as follows (each army and IU has a
basic strength of 1, except the USA and USSR IUs with a basic strength of
2):

    a. Find the total strength of the attacker, halving unit strengths if
       their nation's IS is below 7.
    b. Find the strength of the defender, halving unit strength if
       their nation's IS is below 7, doubling unit strength in cities.
    c. Divide the attacker by the defender to give the odds, rounding down
       to the nearest set of odds, eg. 7-2 becomes 3-1.
    d. Roll one die, cross-index the result as follows:

        DE = defending army involved in the battle is removed.
        AE = all attacking armies involved in the battle are removed.
        DR = defending army involved in the battle must move back one or
             two hexes, not through or into enemy ZOC and subject to the
             normal rules of movement. If it cannot it is destroyed.
        AR = as DR but affects all attacking armies involved in the
             battle.

If a DE or DR result occurred, the attacker can move one of his armies
involved in the battle into the vacated hex.

An example of an attack: 3 Mozambique armies (IS5) and the USSR IU are
attacking 1 South African army (IS8) in Kimberley. Attacker strength =
3 x 1 / 2 + 2 = 3.5; defender strength = 1 x 2 = 2. This gives odds of 1-1
(not quite 2-1 so rounded down). A die roll of 4 gives DR, so the South
African army retreats and the Mozambique army moves into Kimberley. As the
South African army cnnot retreat except through enemy ZOC it is
eliminated.

Every army lost in an attack reduces the owning nation's IS by 1. Odds of
4-1 or more mean automatic elimination of the defender. Attacks cannot be
made at less than 1-2.

@{b}4.2.6. Revolution.@{ub} If the IS of a nation is below 4, and if there is not
a revolution already taking place in the country, a check must be made to
see if one begins. At the points 3 to 0 on the IS table there are three
ranges of numbers concerned with revolution. The range to use is indicated
by the presence or absence of a leader or junta in the country. Each army
of the nation not stacked with a leader or junta is then diced for (one
die throw each), a number within the indicated range meaning that the
army is removed and replaced by a rebel army. Each unoccupied city is
diced for in the same way, to determine control.

If the rebels do not have a city they become an abortive revolution, all
their armies are removed and that is the end of it. If, however, they do
have a city they become viable, and each player, except the player with
Political Influence over the original nation, must roll one die to see
who has Political Influence over the rebels, and how much. The highest die
roll then takes control of the rebels. In the case of a draw all players
roll again. The IS of the rebel nation starts as the same point as that of
the original nation, and the treasury of the rebel nation starts at $0.

The rebel nation can now be treated as an ordinary nation, except that
both the rebel and loyal nations can attack each other so long as they are
at least Politically controlled. Declarations of war and Military control
are not necessary.

If all the cities belonging to the loyalist armies are captured and all
the armies destroyed, the revolution is over and all the loyalist markers
are removed. The rebel markers and armies are then replaced by the
loyalist markers and armies, after the rebel turn. The new nation then
plays in the loyalist turn from the next round. This should not alter the
positions.

@{b}4.2.7. Recreating nations.@{ub} If a nation has been completely occupied by
@{i}one@{ui} other nation, that nation can be recreated at the discretion
of the occupying nation. To do this the occupying nation must be under at
least Political control.

In the turn of the occupying nation the player announces his intention to
recreate. The IS and PI of the created nation are the same as those of the
creating nation, and the treasury of the created nation is $0.

@{b}4.2.8. Ending of wars.@{ub} A war between African nations can come to an end in
one of three ways:

     a. By actual agreement between the combatants.
     b. If either combatant is destroyed.
     c. If, at the end of the Player Powers phase, the nation that
        declared war is no longer under Military control.

@{b}4.2.9. Anomalies in wars.@{ub} Due to stringent requirements to be met before
attacks can be made, there can arise some situations where one side can
attack but not the other. This is quite deliberate. The situations are
listed below where the defender cannot attack back when attacked.

     a. When PI is less than 4.
     b. When in a foreign country and PI is less than 7.
     c. When in a foreign country and the declared war has ceased.

@{b}4.3. Leader/Junta Elimination.@{ub} In this phase each player can attempt to
destroy one leader or junta, if they wish. The players elect verbally who
are attempting to eliminate, and roll one die. A junta is eliminated on a
6, a leader on a 5 or 6.

@{b}4.4.@{ub} The play of the round is now complete, and a new round is begun (see
4).

@{b}5. Victory Conditions.@{ub} This game can be played for 2-99 rounds,
although 10 is a good number to play, giving about a three hour game. If
during that time any player can claim the requisite number of victory
points he is declared the outright winner, otherwise it is the player with
the most victory points at the end who has won.

One victory point is given for each point for each marker on the PI table,
eg. UK starts off with 3+2+3+4=12 victory points.

The victory points needed for an outright win depend upon the number of
players, as follows:

     2 players = 60 victory points.
     3 players = 40 victory points.
     4 players = 30 victory points.
     5 players = 24 victory points.

