@node Original "Original Rulebook"

@{b}RULES@{ub}

@{b}1. Introduction.@{ub} In this game each player takes the role of one of the
powers attempting to establish or maintain a sphere of influence in the
southern half of the African continent. By interfering in the economic
stability and political alliance of nations, and by subsidising them, the
players attempt to extend their political control of Africa, while
diminishing the control of their opponents.

There is the opportunity to set up governments in favour of the players,
encourage revolutions, start wars between the African nations and even
introduce armies of the player-powers into the continent.

@{b}2. Equipment.@{ub} The following equipment is needed to play this game:

    the board;
    154 playing pieces;
    this set of rules;
    scrap paper & pencils;
    a die.

@{b}2.1. The Pieces.@{ub} The pieces are of the following types:

    +-------+    +-------+    +-------+    +-------+    +-------+
    |       |    | ____  |    |       |    |       |    | ____  |
    |       |    | |\\/|  |    |       |    |       |    | |\\/|  |
    | Gabon |    | |/\\|  |    | Junta |    |Leader |    | |/\\|  |
    |       |    |       |    |       |    |       |    |       |
    |       |    | Namib |    |       |    |       |    |       |
    +-------+    +-------+    +-------+    +-------+    +-------+
      Marker       Army         Junta       Leader     Intervention
                                                           unit

@{b}2.2. The Board.@{ub} The board has the following details:

    A map of southern Africa adapted to a hexagon format;
    a national stability table;
    a reference list of costs;
    a national treasury table;
    a random events table;
    a combat results table;
    a political influence table.

@{b}3. Initial Setup.@{ub} Each player selects one of the Player Powers by some
random method. The following Powers should be in play:

    @{u}No. of players    Powers@{uu}
          2           USA, USSR.
          3           USA, USSR, China.
          4           USA, USSR, China, France.
          5           USA, USSR, China, France, UK.

Place one marker for each Power in player on the National Treasury table
at zero.

Then the African nations are set up, as follows:

    a. place one marker for each nation on the Political Influence table.
    b. place one marker for each nation on the Internal Stability table.
    c. place one marker for each nation on the National Treasury table at
       zero.
    d. place the number of armies indicated for that nation within the
       nation's boundaries. (Exceptions: South Africa can set up in
       Namibia as well as South Africa; Zaire loyal armies cannot set up
       in or next to Lumbumbashi, and the Zaire rebels must set up in this
       area.)
    e. place any Leader or Junta indicated in the nation.

The starting positions for the Political Influence and Internal Stability
markers, the initial forces and any Leaders or Juntas are set out in the
table below.

                         Political    Internal     Armed
    @{u}Country              Influence    Stability    Forces    Leader/Junta@{uu}
    South Africa           USA 4          7          10      -
    Namibia                -              -          -       -
    Botswana               UK 3           4          2       -
    Rhodesia-Zimbabwe      USA 4          7          4       USA Leader
    Mozambique             USSR 5         5          4       USSR Junta
    Angola                 USSR 7         4          4       USSR Junta
    Zambia                 UK 2           5          4       UK Leader
    Malawi                 UK 3           5          1       -
    Gabon                  France 5       5          1       France Junta
    Congo                  France 4       4          2       France Leader
    Zaire (loyal)          USA 5          3          4       USA Leader
    Zaire (rebel)          USSR 4         3          2       -
    Tanzania               China 7        6          4       China Junta
    Uganda                 0              3          2       UK Leader
    Kenya                  UK 4           6          4       UK Leader

Armed forces and Leaders and Juntas are always placed by the player with
Political Influence. (Uganda is [initially] placed by UK.) When there are
fewer than 5 players the players dice for the placement of the pieces of
the non-playing Powers. The winner can place the pieces subject to the
following constraints:

    the Leader/Junta [if any] must be placed on a city;
    one army must be placed on each city;
    any excess forces [must be] placed on hexes next to cities @{i}and@{ui}
     next to national borders at the discretion of the placer.

N.B. This dicing for initial placement does not alter the Political
Influence position.

@{b}3.1. Stacking.@{ub} Only one army or intervention unit may occupy a hex,
although a Leader or Junta unit may occupy the same hex as an army.

@{b}4. Order of Play.@{ub}

    a. PLAYER POWERS PHASE:
        i.   Player income;
        ii.  Order writing;
        iii. Order reading and application.
    b. AFRICAN COUNTRIES PHASE:
        i.   Random event;
        ii.  National income;
        iii. Expenditure;
        iv.  Movement of forces;
        v.   Attacks;
        vi.  Supply;
        vii. Revolution Stability check.
    c. LEADER/JUNTA ELIMINATION.

@{b}4.1. Player Powers phase.@{ub} In this phase the players attempt to influence
the African nations. This represents the political interplay of the
powers.

@{b}4.1.1. Player income.@{ub} Each player has the following income each turn, @{i}plus@{ui}
the result of a die roll:

    USA    15;
    USSR   14;
    China  13;
    France 12;
    UK     11.

The Player Power's treasury markers are moved the appropriate number of
points on the National Treasury table, adding on any amounts left from
last turn.

@{b}4.1.2. Order writing.@{ub} Each player writes down, secretly, his expenditure
for that turn. He can spend on:

    Political Influence;
    [Internal] Stability;
    Leaders or Juntas;
    Intervention Units;
    transfers to treasuries of other Players or of African nations.

@{b}4.1.2.1. Political Influence.@{ub} Political Influence (PI) affects the
control that a Player Power can exercise over an African nation. The cost
varies upon the present position on the PI table of the national marker
to be moved. The costs are printed on the board, eg. to move a marker
from position UK5 to UK2 would cost 4+3+3=10; to move it to UK8 would cost
4+5+5=14. Markers can be moved up the player's PI track, or down an
opponent's, or up an ally's, depending on the orders given. If the
movement takes the marker over the zero point then it moves up the track
of the player who has bought most PI points, moving a number of points
equal to the difference between the number of points he has bought and
the number of points his opponent has bought. If there is a draw it
remains at zero. Eg. a marker at UK1 has 1 point bought by UK, 2 points
by USSR, 3 points by USA: so it moves to USA1; if USSR had bought 3 points
it would have moved to zero. Any one marker can be moved no more than 3
points in one turn, either up or down, although players may buy more
points to counteract opponents' orders. It cannot go below zero or above
10.

[In other words, rank the powers by how many points they bought. The 3rd,
4th and 5th power are ignored. The PI marker moves up the track of the 1st
player, by 1st minus 2nd points. A "draw" can be defined by two or more
powers sharing the 1st rank. In this case the PI marker would not change
tracks, it would rest at 0.]

@{b}4.1.2.2. Internal Stability.@{ub} This affects the strength of African nations
and their tendency to revolution. To alter the position of a national
marker on the Internal Stability (IS) table either up or down costs 4.
Any player can buy points to affect any African nation, regardless of the
political affiliation. Any one marker can be moved no more than 3 points
in one turn, either up or down, although players may buy more points to
counteract opponents' orders, and it cannot go above 10 or below zero.

@{b}4.1.2.3. Leaders and Juntas.@{ub} These affect the tendency to revolution of
African nations, and the exertion of Political Influence by the Powers.
They cost 2 each to place, and can only be placed in nations over which
the placing player has Military or Political control. One one Leader or
Junta may be placed in any one country, although two may be placed in a
country in Revolution so long as one only is on each side. They can only
be placed on African armies, and must remain stacked with the army. An
African nation with a Leader/Junta (L/J) unit unit can go up no [Political
Influence] track but that of the L/J owner. It can rest at zero. They have
no effect on combat. They can be destroyed by:

    the army they are stacked with being destroyed;
    a random event (see 4.2.1);
    a successful L/J elimination.

@{b}4.1.2.4. Intervention units.@{ub} These repesent the actual military presence
of soldiers of the Power involved (eg. Cubans in Angola). They cost 4 for
the USA and USSR to build and maintain each turn, and 2 for China and
France. UK does not have an Intervention unit (IU), the others have only
one. They must be placed on or next to a city over which the player
involved has Military control, and must draw their supply from that city,
or one also under Military control. They should be "attached" to the
forces of the country in which they have been placed, and move, attack and
check supply with that country's forces. The African nation does not
maintain them, however, as this is done by the Player Power. Their loss
does not affect the IS of the nation to which they are attached. They
always have full strength in combats (see IS table). They are removed, at
the order reading stage, if:

    a. The player has not maintained them that turn.
    b. The nation to which they were attached is no longer under Military
       control.

If they are removed as above or by combat they can be rebuilt on the
following turn.

@{b}4.1.2.5. Treasury Transfers.@{ub} These are simple to carry out. An order
stating the amount and receiver is written, and in the order reading stage
the amount is deducted from the player's Treasury and added to the
receiving Treasury. There are no limits on this, except that African
nations can never transfer money out, only in.

@{b}4.1.3. Order reading and application.@{ub} When all the players are satisfied
with their orders, they read them out, in turn. The order of reading is
unimportant. The orders are applied subject to the restrictions given
above, and the appropriate markers adjusted.

@{b}4.2. African Countries Phase.@{ub} In this phase the African nations are played
one by one, under the guidance of the players. The player with Political
Influence plays the nation; if no one has PI in the nation then anyone can
play it, as the things that can be done are non-controversial. The nations
are played in the order printed on the board (South Africa to Kenya) with
the rebels played at the end, although it is possible for two or more
nations to conduct joint operations by playing all together in the turn of
the last nation in the joint operation, and forfeiting their individual
turns. Joint operations to be carried out should be announced in the turn
of the first nation in the joint operation. N.B. Each nation or joint
operation conducts all its activities before the next begins.

@{b}4.2.1. Random Event.@{ub} One die is rolled. If it is 6 then a random event has
occurred for that nation, and the die is rolled again. This is indexed on
the Random Events table, and the result carried out. N.B. all nations in a
joint operation must roll separately for their Random Events.

@{b}4.2.2. Nation Income.@{ub} Each city owned by the African nation, whether on
home or foreign soil, gives an income of 2 to its owner, except Zomba and
Libreville which give an income of 1. This is added to any amount already
in the National Treasury, and the National Treasury marker adjusted
accordingly. N.B. Nations in joint operations still receive their incomes
separately.

@{b}4.2.3. Expenditure.@{ub} The African nations can now spend on the following
items:

    maintenance of national forces;
    raising new forces;
    declaring war; or
    simply keeping an unspent reserve

(a list of costs is on the board). Nations in joint operations calculate
their expenditures separately. A nation can never exceed the amount in its
National Treasury; loans or gifts at this stage are not allowed.

@{b}4.2.3.1. Maintenance of National Forces.@{ub} If not maintained the appropriate
army is removed. IS falls one point for every army lost this way.

@{b}4.2.3.2. Raising New Forces.@{ub} This can only be done if the nation is under
Political or Military control. The new army must be built on or next to
home cities and not in enemy zones of control. The maximum number of
armies of a nation (ie. its number of pieces) cannot be exceeded. Raising
new forces does not raise the IS.

@{b}4.2.3.3. Declaring War.@{ub} This can only be done by a nation under military
control. Without such control, operations against other nations (movement
and attacks) other than within the home borders cannot be carried out.
Wars are declared against nations, not against geographical countries; if
a nation occupies more than one country one declaration of war is
sufficient.

@{b}4.2.4. Movement of Forces.@{ub} Only nations under political or military
control can do this. Each army moves up to 5 hexes, subject to the
following restrictions:

     a. An army must stop when it enters an opponent's zone of control.
     b. It may not cross national boundaries unless the nation owning the
        unit has declared war on the nation across the boundary, or the
        owning nation also owns all the cities across the boundary, or the
        nation across the boundary is under a friendly military control
        and is amenable to such an incursion.
     c. Cities do not affect movement.
     d. Pieces do not have to move.

@{b}4.2.4.1. Zones of Control.@{ub} These are the 6 hexes around the hex an army is
in. They do not extend anywhere the army cannot move to. Enemy cities can
be captured by being placed under a friendly Zone of Control (ZOC), but if
there is an opponent's ZOC also extended over the city it must be occupied
by a friendly army.

@{b}4.2.5. Attacks.@{ub} Attacks can be made against pieces on neighbouring hexes;
it is not necessary to make all possible attacks. An attack can be made by
several pieces against one, or one against one, but not one against
several. Each piece can attack only once per turn, although it may be
attacked several times. For a nation to attack enemy armies in its
homeland it must be under at least political control. For a nation to
attack enemy armies outside its homeland it must be under military control
and have declared war on the enemy.

The result of the attack is calculated as follows (each army and IU has a
basic strength of 1, except the USA and USSR IUs with a basic strength of
2):

    a. Find the total strength of the attacker, halving unit strengths if
       their nation's IS is below 7.
    b. Find the strength of the defender, halving unit strength if
       their nation's IS is below 7, doubling unit strength in cities.
    c. Divide the attacker by the defender to give the odds, rounding down
       to the nearest set of odds, eg. 7-2 becomes 3-1.
    d. Roll one die, cross-index the result as follows:

        DE = defending army involved in the battle is removed.
        AE = all attacking armies involved in the battle are removed.
        DR = defending army involved in the battle must move back one or
             two hexes, not through or into enemy ZOC and subject to the
             normal rules of movement. If it cannot it is destroyed.
        AR = as DR but affects all attacking armies involved in the
             battle.

If a DE or DR result occurred, the attacker can move one of his armies
involved in the battle into the vacated hex.

An example of an attack: 3 Mozambique armies (IS5) and the USSR IU are
attacking 1 South African army (IS8) in Kimberley. Attacker strength =
3 x 1 / 2 + 2 = 3.5; defender strength = 1 x 2 = 2. This gives odds of 1-1
(not quite 2-1 so rounded down). A die roll of 4 gives DR, so the South
African army retreats and the Mozambique army moves into Kimberley. As the
South African army cannot retreat except through enemy ZOC it is
eliminated.

Every army lost in an attack reduces the owning nation's IS by 1. Odds of
4-1 or more mean automatic elimination of the defender. Attacks cannot be
made at less than 1-2.

@{b}4.2.6. Supply.@{ub} All the units of the nation, and any IU attached to the
nation, must be able to trace a line of hexes of any length back to a
friendly city. This line of supply must not go over hexes occupied by
enemy pieces or by enemy ZOC, or over hexes in nations against which war
has not been declared unless that nation is under friendly military
control, or all the cities in that nation are occupied by the supplying
nation. Any army that cannot trace this supply line is removed, and the
IS for the nation is moved down one point for every army removed in this
way.

@{b}4.2.7. Revolution.@{ub} If the IS of a nation is below 4, and if there is not
a revolution already taking place in the country, a check must be made to
see if one begins. At the points 3 to 0 on the IS table there are three
ranges of numbers concerned with revolution. The range to use is indicated
by the presence or absence of a leader or junta in the country. Each army
of the nation not stacked with a leader or junta is then diced for (one
die throw each), a number within the indicated range meaning that the
army is removed and replaced by a rebel army. Each unoccupied city is
diced for in the same way, to determine control.

If the rebels do not have a city they become an abortive revolution, all
their armies are removed and that is the end of it. If, however, they do
have a city they become viable, and each player, except the player with
Political Influence over the original nation, must roll one die to see
who has Political Influence over the rebels, and how much. Each player
adds one to his roll for each point that he bought to reduce the IS of the
original nation during the Player Powers phase of that turn only. The
highest adjusted die roll then takes control of the rebels, and places a
rebel marker on his PI track at the place indicated by the adjusted die
roll. In the case of a draw all players roll again. A marker is also
placed on the IS track at the same point as that of the original nation,
and one is placed on the Treasury track at zero.

The rebel nation can now be treated as an ordinary nation, except that
both the rebel and loyal nations can attack each other so long as they are
at least politically controlled. Declarations of war and military control
are not necessary.

If all the cities belonging to the loyalist armies are captured and all
the armies destroyed, the revolution is over and all the loyalist markers
are removed. The rebel markers and armies are then replaced by the
loyalist markers and armies, after the rebel turn. The new nation then
plays in the loyalist turn from the next round. This should not alter the
positions, it is only a convenient way to recycle the rebel pieces.

@{b}4.2.8. Recreating nations.@{ub} If a nation has been completely occupied by
@{i}one@{ui} other nation, that nation can be recreated at the discretion
of the occupying nation. To do this the occupying nation must be under at
least political control, and must draw no income from the occupied
country for that turn or thereafter. The creating and created nation must
carry out a joint operation for this, in the usual way.

In the turn of the joint operation the player announces his intention to
recreate. He then places markers on the IS and PI tables at the same
point as the creating nation, and a marker on the Treasury track at zero.
The rest of the joint operation is conducted as normal, except that if the
creating nation is not under military control all of its armies must
leave the created nation.

@{b}4.2.9. Ending of wars.@{ub} A war between African nations can come to an end in
one of two ways:

     a. If either combatant is destroyed.
     b. If, at the end of the Player Powers phase, the nation that
        declared war is no longer under Military control.

@{b}4.2.10. Anomalies in wars.@{ub} Due to stringent requirements to be met before
attacks can be made, there can arise some situations where one side can
attack but not the other. This is quite deliberate. The situations are
listed below where the defender cannot attack back when attacked.

     a. When PI is less than 4.
     b. When in a foreign country and PI is less than 7.
     c. When in a foreign country and the declared war has ceased.

@{b}4.3. Leader/Junta Elimination.@{ub} In this phase each player can attempt to
destroy one leader or junta, if they wish. The players elect verbally who
are attempting to eliminate, and roll one die. A junta is eliminated on a
6, a leader on a 5 or 6.

@{b}4.4.@{ub} The play of the round is now complete, and a new round is begun (see
4).

@{b}5. Victory Conditions.@{ub} This game can be played for any number of rounds,
although 10 is a good number to play, giving about a three hour game. If
during that time any player can claim the requisite number of victory
points he is declared the outright winner, otherwise it is the player with
the most victory points at the end who has won.

One victory point is given for each point for each marker on the PI table,
eg. UK starts off with 3+2+3+4=12 victory points.

The victory points needed for an outright win depend upon the number of
players, as follows:

     2 players = 60 victory points.
     3 players = 40 victory points.
     4 players = 30 victory points.
     5 players = 24 victory points.

