@node Differences "Differences"

The following rules of the original game are not currently implemented:

    . joint orders.
    . supply.
    . a flat PI application rate of $4 per point is used, rather than a
      variable PI application rate of $3-$5 per point.
    . a straightforward "first come, first served" policy is applied for
      3-or-more-way applications of PI, rather than the system outlined in
      the original rules.
    . application of Political Influence on behalf of other players is not
      supported.
    . armies (European and African) should be allowed to attack in any
      order.
    . adjustments to rebel control according to spending on PI that turn.
    . 4.2.8: "if the creating nation is not under military control all of
      its armies must leave the created nation." This rule is not
      implemented.
    . when granting indendence, it should be done as a joint operation
      (we do it instead at the end of the conqueror's turn), and the
      creating nation should not receive income for those cities that turn
      (or thereafter, of course).
    . 3: we don't implement the restrictions on setup of "extra" mandated
      armies (ie. after cities have armies in them).
    . altered rule 4.2.4b is that:
        a) the destination hex must be owned (home or conquered) by that
           African; or
        b) the destination hex must be owned (home or conquered) to an
           African under your (European player for this African) military
           control; or
        c) the moving African must have declared war against the African
           owner of the country in which the destination hex is.
    . voluntary ending of wars (ie. by agreement).
    . in the real game, "any" player must play the nation if no one has
      influence, which arguably permits sabotage by failure to maintain
      armies. In this version, the Amiga handles army maintenance for
      nations not under at least Political control.
    . in the real game, armies of nations under the political influence of
      non-playing Powers are placed by a random player subject to certain
      restrictions. In this version, the Amiga handles setup for nations
      under the political influence of non-playing Powers.
    . the real game has different rules for building IUs and armies: IUs
      can be built on or next to any militarily controlled city, armies
      must be built on or next to any home city. Our interpretation is:
      these units must be built on or next to any home city.

The following rules of the original game are ambiguous. If you can help
clarify any of these, please do. Listed are the ambiguous rule, and the
current interpretation of it:

    . checking whether an action is allowed, and calculation of the
      costs of an action: this is done at the time the order is written
      (ie. decided upon), not read (ie. carried out).
    . a $24 treasury limit for both players and Africans is enforced.
      (The rules do not mention any limit but provision is only made for
      $24 on the board.)
    . 4.2.7: "a check must be made to see whether one begins...each
      army...is then diced for" this may imply that a separate check must
      be made, and only if that succeeds we should dice for each army and
      each city?
    . are conquered countries (eg. Namibia at start of game) considered
      to be foreign, eg. for purposes of army maintenance? (No, they are
      generally not considered to be foreign).
    . may armies be built in conquered countries? (Yes.)
    . when is the IS lost for not maintaining armies? (a) before or (b)
      after building new armies? (a).
    . the reference to amenability in 4.2.4b seems to imply that another
      "European" player is involved, rather than another African country.
    . what is an "enemy" considered to be, for ZOC purposes? (Anyone not
      under at least our Political control.)
    . when you conquer a country do you get its treasury? (No.)
    . can IUs can take possession of cities on behalf of their African
      host? (Yes.)
    . in African phase, are maintenance, building, and declaring wars done
      in a strict fixed order, as implemented here? Or should there
      ideally be discretion to the player about the order in which things
      are done?
    . are (a) all attack orders made for that African, then all combats
      are conducted, or is (b) each combat conducted immediately after the
      order is given? (a).
    . 4.2.3.3: is (a) movement of IUs/armies within conquered countries
      still allowed, or (b) or are the "home borders" considered to
      include conquered countries? (a).
    . is there a limit to the number of revolutions that may be in
      progress simultaneously? The rules do not mention any limit, but
      only 3 sets of rebel counters are provided. (No limit.)
    . what are the maximum number of armies permitted for rebels? Can they
      "borrow" unused counters from the other 2 sets of rebel counters?
      (We use 5 armies (corresponding to the number of armies provided per
      rebel set), or the maximum number of armies for the loyal government
      of that nation, whichever is lower.)
    . 4.2.6. "Every army lost in an attack reduces the owning nation's IS
      by 1." Does this refer only to attackers or to both attackers and
      defenders? (To both).
    . The conditions to be met for a nation to be conquered are not
      specified anywhere. (All cities captured and all armies destroyed).
    . may IUs be built in an enemy ZOC? (No.)
    . Is an attached IU sufficient to prevent a nation from being
      conquered? (No.)
    . Is it possible to attack an army that is standing on neutral soil?
      Do we need to be at war with the "army owner country" AND the "soil
      country"? (We are assuming only the need to be at war with the "army
      owner country".)
@endnode
